description: Yugi-Kaiba is the first Yu-Gi-Oh! TCG format, including only Legend of Blue-Eyes White Dragon (LOB) and the first Starter Decks: Yugi (SDY) and Kaiba (SDK). There are a few Effect Monsters, a handful of powerful Normal Spells, and simple spot removal. Battle Phase dynamics are important, with cards like Waboku and Reinforcements to consider. This is Yu-Gi-Oh! in its simplest form. Some affectionately call it "chess".
name: Yugi-Kaiba

description: Critter, named after the OCG's Sangan, is the second Yu-Gi-Oh! TCG format. Since Yugi-Kaiba Format, only Metal Raiders (MRD) was introduced. Notable additions include many new Effect Monsters, Heavy Storm, and Solemn Judgment. For the first time, we see a split in play-styles between Aggro and Control. Players can set up win conditions via OTKs, and more powerful Effect Monsters create interesting dynamics.
name: Critter

description: Treasure, named after the OCG's hand-disruption Spells, is a Duel Monsters era format that predates the first ban list. Since Critter Format, Tournament Pack 1 (TP1) and Magic Ruler (MRL) were introduced. Notable additions include Mechanicalchaser, the hand-disruption spells, Quick-Play Spells, Continuous Spells, Painful Choice, recruiter Monsters, and Ritual Monsters. The hand-disruption Spells put a premium on going first, and they have a great effect on deck-building.
name: Treasure

description: Imperial, named after Imperial Order, is a Duel Monsters era format that predates the first ban list. Since Treasure Format, Tournament Pack 2 (TP2) and Pharaoh’s Servant (PSV) were introduced. Notable additions include Morphing Jar, Jinzo, Nobleman of Crossout, Premature Burial, Call of the Haunted, Gravity Bind, and Imperial Order. This format introduces the first good counter to power Spells in Imperial Order, and the game’s first common boss Monster in Jinzo.
name: Imperial

description: Android, named after the OCG's Jinzo, is a Duel Monsters era format that predates the first ban list. Since Imperial Format, Labyrinth of Nightmare (LON)  and Tournament Pack 4 (TP4) were introduced. Notable additions include Gemini Elf, Bazoo the Soul-Eater, Kycoo the Ghost Destroyer, Skull Lair, and Torrential Tribute. Due to mistranslations, cards such as Skull Lair are able to banish any card from the Graveyard instead of only Monster cards as intended.
name: Android

description: Joey-Pegasus is a Duel Monsters era format that predates the first ban list. Since Android Format, the second wave of Starter Decks: Joey (SDJ) and Pegasus (SDP), were introduced. Notable additions include Graceful Charity, Sinister Serpent, Scapegoat, and Harpie’s Feather Duster. This is one of the only formats to feature 2 copies of Graceful Charity.
name: Joey-Pegasus

description: Fiber is a Duel Monsters era format that predates the first ban list. Since Joey-Pegasu Format, Legacy of Darkness (LOD) was introduced. Notable additions include Spirit Monsters, Exiled Force, the format’s namesake: Fiber Jar, Injection Fairy Lily, Yata-Garasu, Creature Swap, Reinforcement of the Army, and Drop Off. As in Joey-Pegasus Format, Graceful Charity is Semi-Limited here.
name: Fiber

description: Yata is a Duel Monsters era format that predates the first ban list. Since Fiber Format, Pharaonic Guardian (PGD) was introduced. Notable additions include Don Zaloog, Spirit Reaper, Mirage of Nightmare, Ring of Destruction, and the Gravekeeper archetype. The format is dominated by Hand Control, however, decks like Gearfried and Gravekeeper are also quite competitive. Historically, games often ended in "Yata locks", with Yata-Garasu forcing the opponent to skip their Draw Phase every turn.
name: Yata

description: Scientist is a Duel Monsters era format that predates the first ban list. Since Yata Format, Magician’s Force (MFC) and Tournament Pack 4 (TP4) were introduced. Notable additions include Apprentice Magician, Breaker the Magical Warrior, the format’s namesake: Magical Scientist, Tribe-Infecting Virus, and Royal Decree. This is the only format in the history of the game with 3 copies of Magical Scientist, therefore Scientist FTK is quite potent here.
name: Scientist

description: Vampire is a Duel Monsters era format that predates the first ban list. Since Scientist Format, Dark Crisis (DCR) was introduced. Notable additions include D.D. Warrior Lady, the format’s namesake: Vampire Lord, Butterfly Dagger - Elma, Skill Drain, and the Archfiend archetype. Perhaps the most consequential difference with this format is that Magical Scientist is now Limited. Hand Control is largely replaced by Warrior Control, and Zombie is now viable as a rogue deck.
name: Vampire

description: Chaos is a Duel Monsters era format that predates the first ban list. As its name suggests, it includes the addition of Invasion of Chaos (IOC). The format revolves around special summoning two of the most iconic cards ever printed, Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning and Chaos Emperor Dragon - Envoy of the End, by banishing a LIGHT and a DARK monster from your Graveyard. Decks in this format are strong enough to compete with full-power Dragon Ruler decks that came out a decade later.
name: Chaos

description: Warrior is the final Duel Monsters era format and the first to feature a ban list. Since Chaos Format, Ancient Sanctuary (AST), Soul of the Duelist (SOD) and Rise of Destiny (ROD) were introduced, while Chaos Emperor Dragon was Forbidden. Notable additions include D.D. Assailant, the first Monarchs, and Monster Gate. The format’s name comes from the historically successful Warrior Control deck, though the modern metagame is quite diverse. During this format, the Shonen Jump Championship series began, with Metagame.com providing live-coverage, bringing the game to a global audience.
name: Warrior

description: Goat is the first GX era format and one of the most popular retro Yu-Gi-Oh! TCG formats, backed by strong community support. Since Warrior Format, Flaming Eternity (FET) and The Lost Millennium (TLM) were introduced, while Confiscation and The Forceful Sentry were Forbidden, and Delinquent Duo and Graceful Charity were unbanned. Notable additions include Rescue Cat, Brain Control, and Lightning Vortex. The format’s name comes from the historically successful Goat Control deck, however, the modern metagame is dominated by Chaos Turbo and Warrior decks. The format is simple and interactive, requiring players to use skills such as reading, bluffing, and resource management.
name: Goat

description: Cyber is a GX era format that shares a ban list with the more popular Goat Format. As its name suggests, it includes the addition of Cybernetic Revolution (CRV), a set that changed the nature of the game. Notable additions include Cyber Dragon, Cyber End Dragon, Cyber Twin Dragon, Dimension Wall, and Magical Explosion. Cyber Dragon set a new bar for beaters, and the Cyber Dragon Fusion Monsters unlocked the full potential of cards like Cyber-Stein and Metamorphosis. The format is largely regarded as a more explosive version of Goat Format.
name: Cyber

description: Reaper is a GX era format shaped by an aggressive ban list that hit Goat Control and Combo decks like Empty Jar and Stein OTK. Since Cyber Format, Elemental Energy (EEN) and Shadow of Infinity (SOI) were introduced, while “The Trinity” of Delinquent Duo, Graceful Charity, and Pot of Greed were Forbidden. Notable additions include Treeborn Frog, Pot of Avarice, and the Dark World archetype. If playing under the suggested SJC Long Beach event, the “good” Last Will ruling is in effect, which is a major boost to the Stein Monarch deck.
name: Reaper

description: Chaos Return is a GX era format shaped by the return of Graceful Charity and a second Magician of Faith, ushering in a brief period of slower gameplay. Since Reaper Format, Enemy of Justice (EOJ) was introduced, while Dark Hole was Forbidden, and Treeborn Frog and Last Will were Limited. Notable additions include Banisher of the Radiance, Dimensional Fissure, and Macro Cosmos. The format was historically dominated by Chaos decks, most memorably, Chaos Return. As the metagame developed, Chaos Recruiter and Chaos Control decks featuring Royal Decree began to emerge.
name: Chaos Return

description: Stein is a GX era format shaped by an aggressive ban of Chaos Sorcerer, which was previously Unlimited. Since Chaos Return Format, Power of the Duelist (POTD) and Cyberdark Impact (CDIP) were introduced, while Thousand-Eyes Restrict was Forbidden. Notable additions include Chimeratech Overdragon, Future Fusion, Overload Fusion, Chain Strike, and Accumulated Fortune. Now that the “Age of Chaos” had officially come to a close, the format was dominated by decks featuring Cyber-Stein, Monarchs, and Burn strategies.
name: Stein

description: Chimeratech is a GX era format defined by the game’s first “emergency ban”, which hit Cyber-Stein. Since Stein Format, Structure Deck: Machine Re-Volt (SD10) was introduced. Notable additions include Green Gadget, Red Gadget, Yellow Gadget, and support for the Ancient Gear archetype. In the only premier event of the format, Machine OTK decks focused on summoning Chimeratech Overdragon were dominant, but the modern metagame appears to be more diverse.
name: Chimeratech

description: Demise is a GX era format known for its explosive gameplay and open-ended deck building, and it’s very similar to the next format, Trooper. Since Airblade Format, Strike of Neos (STON) was introduced, while Graceful Charity was Forbidden, and Dimension Fusion and Giant Trunade were Limited. Notable additions include D.D. Crow, Advanced Ritual Art, Pulling the Rug, and the Six Samurai archetype.
name: Demise

description: Trooper is a GX era format known for its explosive gameplay and open-ended deck building. Since Demise Format, Force of the Breaker (FOTB) was introduced, while Magical Stone Excavation was “emergency” Limited. Notable additions include Raiza the Storm Monarch, Green Baboon, Defender of the Forest, and the Volcanic archetype. The format was defined by the Destiny HERO engine and the Card Trooper + Machine Duplication combo. It was the final format to feature pre-errata Brain Control and Trap Dustshoot at 3 copies.
name: Trooper

description: Zombie is a GX era format shaped by a dampening of the game’s explosiveness via an aggressive banlist. Since Trooper Format, Tactical Evolution (TAEV) was introduced, while Snatch Steal and Ring of Destruction were Forbidden, and Card Trooper, Brain Control, and Trap Dustshoot were Limited. Notable additions include Elemental HERO Neos Alius, Il Blud, Zombie Master, and Dark Bribe. The metagame was quite diverse, with many decks being able to compete. Notably, the Zombie deck was arguably Tier 1 for the first time, despite several attempts to support it since Pharaonic Guardian.
name: Zombie

description: Perfect Circle is a GX era format known for its methodical gameplay. Since Zombie Format, Gladiator’s Assault (GLAS) and Structure Deck: Rise of the Dragon Lords (SDRL) were introduced. Notable additions include Light and Darkness Dragon, Foolish Burial, Trade-In, Dimensional Prison, and the Gladiator Beast archetype. The metagame is centralized around the Perfect Circle Monarch deck, which uses the Destiny Hero engine combined with Raiza the Storm Monarch and Light and Darkness Dragon to control the game.
name: Perfect Circle

description: DAD Return is a GX era format known for its explosive gameplay. Since Perfect Circle Format, Phantom Darkness (PTDN), a set that changed the nature of the game, has been introduced. Notable additions include Dark Armed Dragon, Allure of Darkness, Dark Grepher, Cyber Valley, and Caius the Shadow Monarch, while Monster Reborn was unbanned. The metagame revolves around the infamous DAD Return deck, which uses Dark Armed Dragon, Dimension Fusion, and Return from the Different Dimension to make explosive pushes.
name: DAD Return

description: Gladiator Format is the final GX era format and it’s defined by the “emergency ban” of Dimension Fusion and the “emergency limit” of Return from the Different Dimension. Since DAD Return, Light of Destruction (LODT) was introduced. Notable additions include the Lightsworn archetype, Honest, Gladiator Beast Gyzarus, Substitoad, and Fossil Dyna. The metagame revolves around the near full-power Gladiator Beast deck, which has access to 3 copies of Cold Wave and 3 copies of Gladiator Beast Bestiari.
name: Gladiator

description: Edison is a 5D’s era format and one of the most popular retro Yu-Gi-Oh! TCG formats, backed by strong community support. Since Lightsworn Format, only Starlight Road was introduced.  The format’s name comes from the 75th Shonen Jump Championship held in Edison, New Jersey, which was won by Jeff Jones’s iconic Quickdraw Plant deck. The modern metagame is dominated by Blackwing, HERO, and Frog variants, with other decks and engines such as Dragon, Fairy, Lightsworn, Machina, Plant, and Zombie being competitive. Edison is well known for its open-ended deck-building and highly diverse metagame.
name: Edison

description: Tengu Plant is the first Zexal era format and one of the more popular retro Yu-Gi-Oh! formats. The latest core set available is Generation Force (GENF). This format’s name comes from the iconic Synchro Plant deck that uses Reborn Tengu and Plant Tuners to make a variety of Synchro monsters, including the very powerful Trishula, Dragon of the Ice Barrier. While the Plant deck dominated historically, many other decks are extremely competitive in the modern metagame, including Agent, T.G. Stun, Hero Beat, and several Chaos variants.
name: Tengu

description: HAT Format is the final Zexal era format and one of the more popular retro Yu-Gi-Oh! TCG formats, backed by strong community support. The format’s name comes from the Hand, Artifact, and Traptrix engines. Since Vegas Format, Dragons of Legend (DRLG) and Primal Origin (PRIO) were introduced. Notable additions include Traptrix Dionaea, Soul Charge, Sylvan support, and the Artifact and Hand archetypes. The modern metagame features diverse decks including Artifact Traptrix, Bujin, Geargia, Mermail, and Spellbook. This was the last format before Pendulum Monsters and the removal of First Turn Draw.
name: HAT
